      "date": "2019-08-10 09:33:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nA small question: why we use lowercase facet for FSTYPE and uppercase for VERSION? e.g. $ost1_FSTYPE and $OST1_VERSION?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "bbcfaaafff2c45746cab6bca79ed91f224203a1a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 111,
        "name": "Sarah Liu",
        "email": "sarah@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "sarah"
      },
      "date": "2019-08-13 18:13:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "db6ffbfc54a6728fbcd33b621a74e03c87c18059",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 292,
        "name": "James Nunez",
        "email": "jnunez@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jnunez"
      },
      "date": "2019-08-13 18:54:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nEmoly - Great question. For global variables, we should be using all capitalized letters in the Lustre test scripts. This is why The MGS_VERSION, OST1_VERSION, etc. are all in caps. \n\nWe used lower case letters for the FSTYPE variables because they already existed prior to when we created get_lustre_env() and wanted to be consistent and not break anything in the short term. \n\nFor now, we are using the mixed case due to the legacy use of the FSTYPE variables. We could change this in the future.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
